subsection.p:
It is often the case that more than two variables are related in a predictive way. Consider, for example, a balloon filling with air. To keep the model simple, assume the balloon is always a sphere but with a changing radius. The radius r and volume V of the balloon are related through the equation for volume of a sphere, V = \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3. Notice that this equation is written with the dependent variable V as an explicit function of the independent variable r. By solving for r, we can also write r as an explicit function of V. 
             V &= \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3\qquad \hbox{(Multiply by 3)} 
             3V &= 4 \pi r^3 \qquad \hbox{(Divide by $4 \pi$)} 
             r^3 &= \frac{3V}{4 \pi} \qquad \hbox{(Inverse equation: cube root)} 
             r &= \sqrt[3]{\frac{3V}{4 \pi}} 
         In this new equation, we have the dependent variable r as a function of the independent variable V.
